<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 2.2 - Matrix multiplication and linear combinations</title>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>Find the matrix product</p>
      <p><m>
  \ds
  \left[
    \begin{array}{cccc}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \\
      -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  \fourvec31{-1}1
  </m></p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p><md>
        \left[
    \begin{array}{cccc}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \\
      -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  \fourvec31{-1}1 \\
  = 3\threevec{1}{2}{-1} + \threevec{2}{4}{-2} - \threevec{0}{-3}{6} + \threevec{-1}{-2}{1} \\
  = \left[
    \begin{array}{cccc}
      3 + 2 - 0 - 1 \\
      6 + 4 + 3 - 2 \\
      -3 - 2 - 6 + 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] = \threevec{4}{11}{-10}
      </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose that <m>A</m> is the matrix
  <md>
  A =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{ccc}
      3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp -2 \amp 4 \\
      2 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\
      1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </md>
  If <m>A\xvec</m> is defined, what is the dimension of the vector <m>\xvec</m>?
  What is the dimension of <m>A\xvec</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <solution component="08-solutions">
      <p>
        The dimension of <m>\xvec</m> is 3 (or a <m>3 \times 1</m> matrix). 
      </p>
      <p>
        The dimension of <m>A\xvec</m> is 4 (or a <m>4 \times 1</m> matrix). 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>A vector whose entries are all zero is denoted by
  <m>\zerovec</m>.  If <m>A</m> is a matrix, what is the
  product <m>A\zerovec</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>A\zerovec = \zerovec</m>.  This is because, if <m>A = [ \vvec_1 \,\,\, \vvec_2 \,\,\, \cdots \,\,\, \vvec_n]</m>,
        then <m>{A\zerovec = 0\vvec_1 + 0\vvec_2 + \cdots + 0\vvec_n = \zerovec}</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose that
  <m>I =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
  and that <m>\xvec=\threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3}</m>.  Find the product
  <m>I\xvec</m>
  and explain why <m>I</m> is called the
  <em>identity matrix</em>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>I\xvec = x_1\threevec{1}{0}{0} + x_2\threevec{0}{1}{0} + x_3\threevec{0}{0}{1} = \threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3} = \xvec.</m> 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>I</m> is called the <em>identity matrix</em> because it doesn't change the vector <m>\xvec</m> when multiplied. 
        (Kind of like multiplying any single value by the number 1.)
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose we write the matrix <m>A</m> in terms of its columns
  as 
  <md>
  A =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr}
      \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \vvec_n \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </md>
  If the vector
  <m>\evec_1 =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0
    \end{array}
  \right]</m>, what is the product
  <m>A\evec_1</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>A\evec_1 = 1\vvec_1 + 0\vvec_2 + \cdots + 0\vvec_n = \vvec_1</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose that
  <md>
  A =
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr}
      1 \amp 2 \\
      -1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right],
  \bvec = \left[
    \begin{array}{r}
      6 \\ 0
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </md>
  Is there a vector <m>\xvec</m> such that <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m>?  Explain your
  process for answering this question clearly. Hint: Use <m>\xvec = \twovec{x_1}{x_2}</m> and write out <m>A\xvec</m> as a linear combination.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Following the hint we have the following matrix multiplication for <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m>:
        <md>
          \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr}
      1 \amp 2 \\
      -1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]\twovec{x_1}{x_2} = \left[
    \begin{array}{r}
      6 \\ 0
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        This then corresponds to the equivalent linear combination of:
        <md>
          x_1\twovec{1}{-1} + x_2\twovec{2}{1} = \twovec{6}{0}.
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        This then gives the linear system of 
      <md>
        \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    x_1 \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2x_2 \amp  {}={}  \amp 6 \\
    -x_1 \amp  {}+{}  \amp x_2 \amp  {}={}  \amp 0 \\
    \end{alignedat}
      </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        And it's corresponding augmented matrix:
        <md>
\left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 6 \\
      -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Solving this using Gaussian Elimination/Sage we have:
        <md>
\left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 6 \\
      -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
        Such that there is a unique solution with <m>\xvec = \twovec{x_1}{x_2} = \twovec{2}{2}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We can check this by performing the following matrix multiplication:
      <md>
          \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr}
      1 \amp 2 \\
      -1 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]\twovec{2}{2} = \left[
    \begin{array}{r}
      6 \\ 0
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <remark>
  <p>In <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0Ng" visual="gvsu.edu/s/0Ng">Sage</url>, we
  may define a vector as <c>v = vector([2, 3, -1]).</c>
  </p>
  <p>
    Scalar multiplication, vector addition, and matrix multiplication work just as
    you would expect: <c>3*v, v + x,</c> and <c>A*v</c>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also, if <c>A</c> is a matrix and <c>b</c> is a vector, then
    <c>A.augment(b)</c>
    gives the new matrix obtained by augmenting <c>A</c> by the vector <c>b</c>.
  </p>
</remark>

<exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>In Sage, define the following matrix and vectors:
  <md>
  A = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      -2 \amp 0 \\
      3 \amp 1 \\
      4 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right], \vvec = \twovec{-2}{3}, \wvec = \twovec{1}{2}.
  </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Compare the result of evaluating <m>A(3\vvec)</m> to that of evaluating <m>3A\vvec</m>.
        (Don't forget Sage doesn't recognize ( ) as multiplication, use *, which is above the 8 on
        your keyboard.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>A(3\vvec) = 3A\vvec = \threevec{12}{-9}{-6}</m>
        </p>
        <sage>
<input>
A = matrix(3,2,[-2,0,3,
                1,4,2])
v = vector([-2,3])
w = vector([1,2])
print(A*(3*v))
print(3*(A*v))
</input>
<output>
(12, -9, -6)
(12, -9, -6)
</output>
</sage>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compare the result of evaluating <m>A(\vvec + \wvec)</m> to that of evaluating <m>A\vvec + A\wvec</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>A(\vvec + \wvec) = A\vvec + A\wvec = \threevec{2}{2}{6}</m> - these are equal by the distributive property!
        </p>
        <sage>
<input>
A = matrix(3,2,[-2,0,3,
                1,4,2])
v = vector([-2,3])
w = vector([1,2])
print(A*(v+w))
print(A*w+A*v)
</input>
<output>
(2, 2, 6)
(2, 2, 6)
</output>
</sage>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Suppose that <m>A</m> is the matrix
  <md>
  A = \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \\
      -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Describe the solution space to the equation
  <m>
  A\xvec = \threevec{-1}15.
  </m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><md>
          \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
      -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
        No solution since there is a pivot in the rightmost column of the augmented matrix.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Describe the solution space to the equation
  <m>
  A\xvec = \threevec36{-3}.
  </m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><md>
          \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp 6 \\
      -1 \amp -2 \amp 6 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
        There are infinitely many solutions because there are two free variables <m>{(x_2, x_4)}</m> and the system is consistent.
      </p>
      <p>
        In parametric form, we have <m>x_1 = -2x_2 + x_4 + 3</m> and <m>x_3 = 0</m>.  This yields an
        infinite solution set of 
        <md>
          \xvec = \fourvec{-2x_2 + x_4 + 3}{x_2}{0}{x_4}.
        </md>
      </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <remark>
    <p>
      Given two matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, we can form the product <m>AB</m> by multiplying
      the columns of <m>B</m> by <m>A</m>. That is, let
      <md>
        B = [ \bvec_1 \,\,\, \bvec_2 \,\,\, \cdots \,\,\, \bvec_p]
      </md>
      then, 
      <md>
       AB = [ A\bvec_1 \,\,\, A\bvec_2 \,\,\, \cdots \,\,\, A\bvec_p].
      </md>
      To do this, the number of columns of <m>A</m> must equal the number of rows of <m>B</m>.
    </p>
  </remark>

  <example xml:id="ex-mat-mult">
  <title>Matrix Multiplication</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Given the matrices
      <md>
        A = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      4 \amp 2  \\
      0 \amp 1  \\
      -3 \amp 4 \\
      2 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right], \,\,\, B = \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr}
      -2 \amp 3 \amp 0  \\
      1 \amp 2 \amp -2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
      </md>
      we have
      <md>
      <mrow>
        AB = \amp \left[ A\twovec{-2}{1} \,\,\, A\twovec{3}{2} \,\,\, A\twovec{0}{-2}\right]
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
         = \amp \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr}
      -6 \amp 16 \amp -4  \\
      1 \amp 2 \amp -2  \\
      10 \amp -1 \amp -8 \\
      -4 \amp 6 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>

<exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider <xref ref="ex-mat-mult"/> which has the following matrix as its result:   
  <md>
        AB = \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr}
      -6 \amp 16 \amp -4  \\
      1 \amp 2 \amp -2  \\
      10 \amp -1 \amp -8 \\
      -4 \amp 6 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
      </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain where the <m>-6</m> in the top left comes from.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's consider the first column of <m>AB</m>, which corresponds to multiplying <m>A</m> by the first column of <m>B</m>:
          <md>
            A\twovec{-2}{1} = -2\fourvec{4}{0}{-3}{2} + \fourvec{2}{1}{4}{0} = \fourvec{-8+2}{0+1}{6+4}{-4+0} = \fourvec{-6}{1}{10}{-4}.
          </md>
          This yields the <m>-6</m> in the top left.  It comes from multiplying the first column of <m>B</m> with the first row of <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What about the 0 in the bottom right?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's consider the third column of <m>AB</m>, which corresponds to multiplying <m>A</m> by the third column of <m>B</m>:
          <md>
            A\twovec{0}{-2} = 0\fourvec{4}{0}{-3}{2} - 2\fourvec{2}{1}{4}{0} = \fourvec{-4}{-2}{-8}{0}.
          </md>
          This yields the <m>0</m> in the bottom right.  It comes from multiplying the third column of <m>B</m> with the last row of <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Suppose that    
  <md>
        A = \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr}
      1 \amp 3 \amp 2  \\
      -3 \amp 4 \amp -1  \\
    \end{array}
  \right], \,\,\,\,\, B = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 0   \\
      1 \amp 2  \\
      -2 \amp -1  \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
      </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Before computing, first explain why the shapes of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> 
          enable us to form the product <m>AB</m>.  Then describe the shape of <m>AB</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The number of columns of <m>A</m> is equal to the number of rows of <m>B</m>,
          so we are able to perform matrix multiplication. Matrix multiplication is equivalent
          to multiplying each column of <m>B</m> by <m>A</m>.  Since <m>A</m> has 2 rows, each
          <m>A\bvec_i</m> will be a vector with 2 rows and with <m>B</m> having two columns, 
          the product <m>AB</m> will have 2 rows and 2 columns.
        </p>
        <p>
          We can also think of the dimensions in the following way.  If <m>A</m> is a <m>2 \times 3</m>
          matrix and <m>B</m> is a <m>3 \times 2</m> matrix, then for the product <m>AB</m>
          we take the dimensions as the "outer" dimensions of both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, which gives
          us a <m>{2 \times 2}</m> matrix.  The "inner" dimensions of both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are 3 and much 
          match in order to complete the matrix multiplication due to the procedure in the paragraph 
          above.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the product <m>AB</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
        AB = \left[ A\threevec{3}{1}{-2} \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, A\threevec{0}{2}{-1} \right].
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Considering each element of the product above separately, we have
          <md>
        A\threevec{3}{1}{-2} = 2\twovec{1}{-3} + \twovec{3}{4} + (-2)\twovec{2}{-1} = \twovec{2}{-3} \\
        A\threevec{0}{2}{-1} = 0\twovec{1}{-3} + 2\twovec{3}{4} + (-1)\twovec{2}{-1} = \twovec{4}{9}
          </md>
          This means that the product <m>AB</m> is
          <md>
            AB = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      2 \amp 4 \\
      -3 \amp 9 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sage can multiply matrices using *. Definte the matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>
          in a Sage cell and check your work by computing <m>AB</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <sage>
<input>
A = matrix(2,3,[1,3,2,
              -3,4,-1])
B = matrix(3,2,[3,0,
                1,2,
              -2,-1])
A*B
</input>
<output>
[2 4]
[-3 9]
</output>
</sage>
        <p>
          We were right!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Are we able to form the matrix product <m>BA</m>? If so, compute <m>BA</m>
          (you can use a Sage cell, or do by hand).  Is it generally true that <m>AB = BA</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Yes! We can compute the matrix product <m>BA</m> because the number of columns of <m>B</m>
          is equal to the number of rows of <m>A</m>.
        </p>
          <sage>
<input>
A = matrix(2,3,[1,3,2,
              -3,4,-1])
B = matrix(3,2,[3,0,
                1,2,
              -2,-1])
B*A
</input>
<output>
[3 9 6]
[-5 11 0]
[1 -10 -3]
</output>
</sage>
        <p>
          Here, <m>BA \neq AB</m> and therefore, it is not generally true that <m>AB = BA</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

   <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Form the matrices   
  <md>
        A = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      1 \amp 2  \\
      -2 \amp -4 \\
    \end{array}
  \right], \,\,\,\,\, B = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      2 \amp -4   \\
      -1 \amp 2  \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
      </md>
      What is the product <m>AB</m> in this case?
    </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            AB = \left[A\twovec{2}{-1} \,\,\,\,\, A\twovec{-4}{2}\right].
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Computing the columns separately we have:
        <md>
          A\twovec{2}{-1} = 2\twovec{1}{-2} + (-1)\twovec{2}{-4} = \twovec{0}{0} \\
          A\twovec{4}{-2} = (-4)\twovec{1}{-2} + 2\twovec{2}{-4} = \twovec{0}{0} \\
        </md>
        This yields 
        <md>
        AB = \left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      0 \amp 0  \\
      0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can also use Sage! 
      </p>
        <sage>
<input>
A = matrix(2,2,[1,2,
              -2,-4])
B = matrix(2,2,[2,-4,
                -1,2])
A*B
</input>
<output>
[0 0]
[0 0]
</output>
</sage>
        <p>
          Note: as this example shows, if the matrix product <m>AB = 0</m>, this does not mean
          that <m>A = 0</m> or <m>B = 0</m> (where here <m>0</m> represents a matrix of all zero entries).
        </p>
      </solution>
  </exercise>

  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What is the connection between the operation <m>A\xvec</m> where <m>A</m> is a matrix and <m>\xvec</m> is a vector and linear combinations?</p></li>
      <li><p>How do solutions to the matrix equation <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m> (where <m>A</m> is a matrix and <m>\bvec</m> is a vector) correspond to solutions of a certain linear system?</p></li>
      <li><p>When can two matrices be multiplied? What will the dimension of their product be?</p></li>
      <li><p>How do we view matrix multiplication as encoding a linear combination? How do we compute matrix products?</p></li>
      <li><p>How do we get Sage to do matrix multiplication?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </outcomes>

</worksheet>
